lowering cost towards ğœŒ = .5 and then rising again until ğœŒ = .75 where ğ‘“ (.75) = 2 = ğ‘“ (0). At this point, another resource ğ‘Ÿ1 is selected for allocation. ğ‘Ÿ1 is preferred over ğ‘Ÿ0 as its cost becomes lower with new allocations so that both loads move towards ğœŒ0 = ğœŒ1 = .5, where both are balanced. Both loads rise again until ğœŒğ‘Ÿ0 = ğœŒğ‘Ÿ1 = .75, where the third resource ğ‘Ÿ2 kicks in. It repeats for ğ‘Ÿ3, but no more idle resource is available when ğœŒ reaches 3.0 so that the loads grow beyond .75 up to ğœŒ = .875 and ğœŒ = 3.5.
When the system load decreases, the process is reversed. After reaching ğœŒ = .5 for all, one resource with the lowest load ğœŒ < .5 becomes more expensive than the others. This one is less preferred for subsequent assignments, and quickly loses the load until it becomes idle again, while the other 3 keep ğœŒ in [.5, .75]. It repeats for the remaining ones.
It is easy to see how the number of active resources changes when there are more resources. When the number of active resources is increasing, the load of each active resource stays at around ğœŒ = .75. On the other hand, when the number of active resources is decreasing, the load of each active resource stays at around ğœŒ = .5. In short, when all resources are equal, the system tries to maintain the load of active resources in the working load range [.5, .75], while keeping idle resources as much as possible.

